  "@type": "Article",
  "dateModified": "2026-03-06",
  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Usability testing is the practice of observing real people as they attempt to use a document, interface, or system — then revising based on where they succeed, hesitate, misread, or fail. In writing, usability testing treats a document as a tool the reader uses to accomplish something, and evaluates whether that tool works.\nJanice Redish argued that written content should be tested the same way software is tested: through observation, not self-report. Readers who struggle with a document often can\u0026rsquo;t articulate what went wrong — they may blame themselves, skip sections, or misunderstand without knowing it. Watching them use the document reveals problems that surveys and self-assessment miss [@redish2012].\n",
